      <div xml:id="NA104-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivi āṟupārttu uṟṟa accattāl colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE says out of the fear she experienced when seeing the path.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA104">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            pūmpoṟi yuḻuvaip pēḻvā yēṟṟai</l>
<l>            tēṅkamaḻ cilampiṟ kaḷiṟṟoṭu poriṉē</l>
<l>            tuṟukaṉ mīmicai yuṟuka ṇañcāk</l>
<l>            kuṟakkuṟu mākkaḷ pukaṟciyi ṉeṟinta</l>
<l>            toṇṭakac ciṟupaṟaip pāṇi yayalatu </l>
<l>            paintāṭ centiṉaip paṭukiḷi yōppu</l>
<l>            mārkali veṟpaṉ mārpunayan tuṟaiyum</l>
<l>            yāṉē yaṉṟiyu muḷarkol pāṉāṭ</l>
<l>            pāmpuṭai viṭara vōṅkumalai miḷira</l>
<l>            vurumuccivan teṟiyum poḻutoṭu perunīr </l>
<l>            pōkkaṟa vilaṅkiya cāra</l>
<l>            ṉōkkaruñ ciṟuneṟi niṉaiyu mōrē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Even apart from me,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">yāṉē aṉṟiyum</term>: a predicateless attributive clause ending in -<term xml:lang="ta">ē</term> followed by <term xml:lang="ta">anṟiyum</term>, what kind of syntax is this?</note></l>
<l>who is longing permanently for the chest of the man from the bustling(?)</l>
<l rend="indent4">mountain<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ārkali veṟpaṉ</term> cf. KT 257.4.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the rhythm of the small Toṇṭakam drum,</l>
<l rend="indent2">beaten joyously by the little people of the hills,</l>
<l rend="indent2">without fearing affliction on the heights of thick stones,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">poriṉē</term>: why here a conditional marked with -<term xml:lang="ta">ē</term>, where it is clearly not the mark of a subject clause? What do these two lines add to the message in any case?</note> the vast-mouthed male of the flower-dotted tiger</l>
<l rend="indent3">fights with the elephant bull on the mountain side fragrant with honey,</l>
<l rend="indent">chases away the parakeets invading the fresh-stalked red millet nearby</l>
<l rend="indent3">– is he [still] thinking<note place="foot">Do we have to read <term xml:lang="ta">niṉaiyumōr uḷar</term> as a kind of complex continuous form? How else could it be understood?</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">of the small path difficult to look at on the slope</l>
<l rend="indent2">that is obstructed, so that going [there] is terminated, by great water</l>
<l rend="indent2">with the time<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">poḻutoṭu</term>: this is not a familiar use of the sociative. It presumably denotes a temporal coincidence: the rain comes at the same time as the thunder. It might, however, also be possible to understand <term xml:lang="ta">poḻutu</term> here in the sense of <term xml:lang="ta">paruvam</term>, as a season.</note> when the thunder dashes angrily so that</l>
<l rend="indent3">the high mountains with caves that possess snakes are upset</l>
<l rend="indent4">at midnight?</l>
        </lg>
